## Scope: What NOT to Include

**Org-mode integration**: Skip this. I don't use Org-mode heavily. For project-specific TODOs and issue tracking, we should use git artemis instead.

**Magit/Git operations**: Don't need dedicated commands. On the rare occasions when git operations through Emacs would be useful, pi can just evaluate the appropriate elisp code (e.g., `(magit-status)`).

**Frame/window management**: Similarly, don't need dedicated commands for saving/restoring window configurations, managing frames, etc. These are edge cases that can be handled via generic elisp evaluation when needed.

**Generic elisp evaluation**: DO include this as a fallback. When pi needs to do something Emacs-related that doesn't have a dedicated command, it can execute arbitrary elisp and get the results back. This provides flexibility without bloating the command set.

Focus on the core workflow: buffer context queries, buffer editing, LSP integration, and navigation. Keep the API lean.
